## Description

- For HTTP-based services,  use the built-in HTTPS handler or the HTTPSClient class in the Android framework. You can call the `java.net.URL` class using a URI that starts with `https://` to use the HTTP-over-TLS (HTTPS) secured communication. Alternative interfaces includes `javax.net.ssl.HttpsURLConnection` and `org.apache.http.client.HttpClient` when used with a URI that starts with `https://` (Android Marshmallow does not support Apache HTTP client. In order to use Apache HTTP APIs, if really needed, specify this in the build.gradle file (compile-time dependency): `android { useLibrary 'org.apache.http.legacy' }`).

- For custom protocols that use TLS, you can use the `SSLSocketFactory` from the `javax.net.ssl` package to make a `SSLSocket`. However, it is extremely crucial to explicitly validate the certificate's common name before sending the data. Unlike HTTPS, the certificate will not be validated against the peer's host name. See the code example below as a sample of how to validate the host name explicitly.

- Note that, the following changes took place in **Android O**:
    - ```HttpURLConnection``` normalizes URL's containing empty paths by appending a slash at the end of them. 
    - ```HttpsURLConnection``` does not allow insecure TLS/SSL fallback.

## Code

For HTTPS protocols:

-- src/com/example/androidssl/AndroidSSL.java

```
// Use the URL class to handle https protocol
URL url = new URL(eText.getText().toString());
URLConnection conn = url.openConnection();

// Get the response
BufferedReader rd = new BufferedReader(new
    InputStreamReader(conn.getInputStream()));
String line = "";
while ((line = rd.readLine()) != null) {
    Message lmsg;
    lmsg = new Message();
    lmsg.obj = line;
    lmsg.what = 0;
    AndroidSSL.this.h.sendMessage(lmsg);
}
Download the Complete Code Exampledownload link

For general SSL-based communication other than HTTP:
```
-- src/com/example/androidssl/AndroidSSL.java
```
SSLContext ssl_context = SSLContext.getInstance("TLS");
ssl_context.init(null, null, null);
SSLSocketFactory socketFactory = ssl_context.getSocketFactory();

// Get the host part
String [] parts = eText.getText().toString().split("//");
String host = parts[parts.length-1];

// Create a SSL Socket
SSLSocket socket = (SSLSocket)socketFactory.createSocket(host, DEFAULT_SSL_PORT);
socket.setSoTimeout(20000);
socket.setUseClientMode(true);
socket.startHandshake();

/*
 * Here we validate the common name (CN) of the peer's certificate against
 * the expected host name. Without this, the any valid certificate can be
 * used by the attacker or the man in the middle!!
 * Since it is not HTTP-based SSL, the library code does not have a way
 * to validate the certificate's CN.
 */
Principal peer_principal = socket.getSession().getPeerPrincipal();
if (peer_principal.getName().indexOf("CN=" + EXPECTED_HOST + ",") == -1) {
    Message lmsg;
    lmsg = new Message();
    lmsg.obj = "ERROR: Host not matching " + EXPECTED_HOST;
    lmsg.what = 0;
    AndroidSSL.this.h.sendMessage(lmsg);
    return;
}

// Send a sample simple request to get the content
socket.getOutputStream().write("GET / HTTP/1.1\r\n\r\n".getBytes("UTF-8"));

// Get the response
BufferedReader rd = new BufferedReader(new
    InputStreamReader(socket.getInputStream()));
String line = "";
while ((line = rd.readLine()) != null) {
    Message lmsg;
    lmsg = new Message();
    lmsg.obj = line;
    lmsg.what = 0;
    AndroidSSL.this.h.sendMessage(lmsg);
}
```
