Developers can use permissions to restrict access to components by other applications (that do not possess the right permissions). It is done by including a permission attribute in the Android Manifest file:

            <activity android:name="myActivity"
            android.permission="android.permission.CAMERA">
            <intent-filter>
            ...
            </intent-filter>
            </activity>

Alternatively a developer can check the callers permissions in the code:

            if (getContext().checkCallingPermission("android.permission.CAMERA") == PackageManager.PERMISSION_GRANTED) {
                    // ... Do something
            }

A similar method `checkCallingOrSelfPermission()` checks if a calling process or the currently active process has a specific permission: 

            int result = checkCallingOrSelfPermission("android.permission.CAMERA");
            if (result==PackageManager.PERMISSION_GRANTED)) { /* do something */ }

Using the `checkCallingOrSelfPermission()` method can result in improper permission re-delegation (or in other words privilege escalation). A malicious application which uses Intents (or other forms of IPC such as binders) to invoke the developer's application can obtain the called application's permissions to access resources without having those permissions itself so it should be used with care.

Developers can also mandate having a permission for any component that receives a broadcast (in the example below, _myIntent_ is only received by those components that have CAMERA permission):

            Intent myIntent = new Intent(MESSAGE_RECEIVED);
            context.sendBroadcast(myIntent, "android.permission.CAMERA");

Path traversal could become a severe problem in Android applications that implement content providers to provide files for other applications based on the input URI.

Follow the steps below to minimize the chance of path traversal when a target filename is created using an input (for example through a content provider URI): 

1. First, decode the input string:

        String decodedInput = Uri.decode(inputUri.toString());

2. Obtain the resource based on the last part of the decoded string in your intended target folder (parentDirectory):

        File targetFile = new File(parentDirectory, Uri.parse(decodedInput).getLastPathSegment());

3. Note that it is possible that you have landed in another directory if the input is double encoded. Compare the absolute path of a file in the parent directory with this file:

        File f=new File(parentDirectory, "AKnownFile.txt");
        String parentAbsoluteDirectory = f.getAbsolutePath();
        if targetFile.getCanonicalPath().equals(parentAbsoluteDirectory) ...

4. Only proceed if these two paths are the same.

You can use the following approach to take photos and upload them to a server without having to save the photos on local storage (which could be accessible by other applications):

1. You will need to use `android.view.SurfaceView`, `android.view.SurfaceHolder` and `android.hardware.Camera` classes.
2. Create a preview of what camera is receiving in the surface viewer. To display a live preview of what the camera is viewing you will need to implement a Callback for android.view.SurfaceHolder (android.view.SurfaceHolder.Callback) as preview class. 
(Callbacks are classes that contain specific methods that are called on your behalf at certain times.) 
3. In surfaceCreated() method of the Callback, get the camera instance and show what it is receiving:

        myCamera = Camera.open();
        myCamera.setPreviewDisplay(myHolder);

4. Make sure that you implement surfaceDestroyed() in the Callback so that it releases the camera resources:

        myCamera.stopPreview();
        myCamera = null;

5. Create a button that when clicked, takes a picture. You will need to call the method takePicture() of class Camera to take a picture. It expects an argument of type Camera.PictureCallback. It is basically what you want to do with the captured data:


     	       PictureCallback rawCallback = new PictureCallback() {
		public void onPictureTaken(byte[] data, Camera camera) {
			// DO WHAT YOU WANT TO DO WITH DATA HERE     }
		}  

6. You can send the data directly to the server without having to save it on the local storage.



For more information, refer to [Android Training on Direct Usage of Camera](http://developer.android.com/training/camera/cameradirect.html).

Implementing browser-based data encryption/decryption using a server-provided key requires the following steps:

* Transform the server-provided key data into a cryptographic key
* Using the key to encrypt and decrypt data

Each of the steps is detailed below, using the Web Crypto API.



__Loading the key__

```
// In reality, this data is received from the server
let initData = {
    rawKey: window.base64js.fromByteArray(window.crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(32))),
    hash: "SHA-256",
    algoName: "AES-GCM",
    algoLength: 256
}

return window.crypto.subtle.importKey(
        "raw",
        window.base64js.toByteArray(initData.rawKey),
        {
            name: initData.algoName,
            length: initData.algoLength
        },
        true,
        ["encrypt", "decrypt"]
    )
```

__Encrypting/Decrypting data__

```
// Uses base64 encoding/decoding from https://github.com/beatgammit/base64-js/releases/tag/v1.3.0

function encrypt(key, data) {
    //IV is supposed to be 12 bytes
    let iv = window.crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(12));
    let encodedText = new TextEncoder().encode(data);

    return window.crypto.subtle.encrypt({
            name: "AES-GCM",
            iv: iv
        },
        key,
        encodedText)
    .then(
        (encryptedData) => {
            let encryptedBytes = new Uint8Array(encryptedData);
            let encryptedBase64 = window.base64js.fromByteArray(encryptedBytes);
            return window.base64js.fromByteArray(iv) + "." + encryptedBase64;
        },
        (error) => {
            throw error;
        });
}

function decrypt(key, data) {
    let b64Iv = data.split(".")[0]
    let b64Data = data.split(".")[1];
    let iv = window.base64js.toByteArray(b64Iv);
    let encryptedBytes = window.base64js.toByteArray(b64Data);

    return window.crypto.subtle.decrypt({
            name: "AES-GCM",
            iv: iv
        },
        key,
        encryptedBytes)
    .then(
        (decryptedData) => {
            let decryptedBytes = new Uint8Array(decryptedData);
            return new TextDecoder("utf-8").decode(decryptedBytes);
        },
        (error) => {
            throw error;
        }
    )
}
```

Implementing browser-based data encryption/decryption using a passphrase requires the following steps:

* Generating a salt
* Transforming the salt and passphrase into a cryptographic key
* Using the key to encrypt and decrypt data

Each of the steps is detailed below, using the Web Crypto API.



__Obtaining a salt__

```
// Retrieve existing initData from storage
let initData;

if(typeof initData === "undefined") {
    // Generate whatever we need to generate a new key and store in initData
    initData = {
        salt: window.crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(16)),
        iterations: 100000,
        hash: "SHA-256",
        algoName: "AES-GCM",
        algoLength: 256
    }
}
```

__Generating the key__

```
// The data containing the algorithm configuration and client-specific salt
let initData = {...};

// The passphrase of the user
let passphrase = "...";

return window.crypto.subtle.importKey(
        "raw",
        new TextEncoder().encode(passphrase),
        {name: "PBKDF2"},
        false,
        ["deriveKey"]
    )
    .then(
        (passwordKey) => {
            return window.crypto.subtle.deriveKey(
                {
                    name: "PBKDF2",
                    salt: initData.salt,
                    iterations: initData.iterations,
                    hash: initData.hash
                },
                passwordKey,
                {
                    name: initData.algoName,
                    length: initData.algoLength
                },
                true,
                ["encrypt", "decrypt"]
            )
        },
        (error) => {
        }
    );
```

__Encrypting/Decrypting data__

```
// Uses base64 encoding/decoding from https://github.com/beatgammit/base64-js/releases/tag/v1.3.0

function encrypt(key, data) {
    //IV is supposed to be 12 bytes
    let iv = window.crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(12));
    let encodedText = new TextEncoder().encode(data);

    return window.crypto.subtle.encrypt({
            name: "AES-GCM",
            iv: iv
        },
        key,
        encodedText)
    .then(
        (encryptedData) => {
            let encryptedBytes = new Uint8Array(encryptedData);
            let encryptedBase64 = window.base64js.fromByteArray(encryptedBytes);
            return window.base64js.fromByteArray(iv) + "." + encryptedBase64;
        },
        (error) => {
            throw error;
        });
}

function decrypt(key, data) {
    let b64Iv = data.split(".")[0]
    let b64Data = data.split(".")[1];
    let iv = window.base64js.toByteArray(b64Iv);
    let encryptedBytes = window.base64js.toByteArray(b64Data);

    return window.crypto.subtle.decrypt({
            name: "AES-GCM",
            iv: iv
        },
        key,
        encryptedBytes)
    .then(
        (decryptedData) => {
            let decryptedBytes = new Uint8Array(decryptedData);
            return new TextDecoder("utf-8").decode(decryptedBytes);
        },
        (error) => {
            throw error;
        }
    )
}
```

