Two classes of `CipherInputStream` and `CipherOutputStream` help manage data as wrappers for other streams. For example, to encrypt or decrypt a file, each of these can simply wrap the resulting stream obtained by the appropriate file input/output utilities. This wrapping can be performed in the same `try` block of the stream, that is `AutoCloseable`.

Cipher streams can transparently encrypt/decrypt data. For example your application can read or write a normal stream without knowing about the underlying cryptography. This can be most helpful when adding encryption to an existing application, as it would not require changes beyond wrapping the stream.

The way that we can wrap a stream is to take the normal stream and initiate the encryption cipher. Then we wrap the stream using the `CipherOutputStream` around the original stream. Then we write into the newly wrapped stream.

Obtain your Input/OutputStream as normal (Here `out` is a normal object, of the class type `OutputStream`). Initiate a cipher:

    final Cipher cipher = Cipher.getInstance("RSA");
    cipher.init(Cipher.ENCRYPT_MODE, key);

Wrap your stream:

    OutputStream wrapped = new CipherOutputStream(out, cipher);

Continue working with the wrapped stream. `CipherInputStream` works exactly the same way and its constructor `CipherInputStream(InputStream is, Cipher c)` gets `InputStream` objects along with a `Cipher` object.

## Description

Avoid hard-coding passwords and secret keys in client code or in any other file accessible on the client in an unencrypted form. Either encrypt the secrets on the client (and follow other guidelines expanded on in another task for storing sensitive data on client and in keystores), or use server side component of the application to store the secrets.

When choosing the second option, store these keys on the server side module of your application and add a step to any process that needs to use these keys to send the request to server-side for signing, encryption, validation, or decryption via the secret key. In the following, we analyze the most common scenario:

There are certain cases such as third party services using OAuth or Single Sign On (SSO) services that the mobile app needs to sign and validate messages for communicating with a third party application. In such a case, each client application has a secret key that is used to sign the requests coming from the application. The workaround to avoid hardcoding this secret in the client side is to move the signing code along with the signature to the server side service.

In the above scenario, client applications send the request to be signed for a third party to the server. The server then validates the session on the client and signs the arguments/token and returns the signature to the client. The client will then send the received signature along with the original arguments to the third party service to establish authenticity.

## Code

The following sample code shows how to sign parameters without hardcoding the secret key on the client code. The signature is displayed at the end for demonstration purposes.

 -- src/com/example/androidssl/AndroidSecretKey.java

            public void onClick(View v) {
                try {
                    tView.setText("");

                    /* Here we will send the data that needs to be signed by a secret key
                     * to the server. This will prevent the need to have the secret key
                     * stored in the client code.
                     */

                    // Create a new HttpClient and Post Header
                    HttpClient httpclient = new DefaultHttpClient();
                    HttpPost httppost = new HttpPost(eText.getText().toString());

                    // Adding HTTP Post parameters
                    List<NameValuePair> nameValuePairs = new ArrayList<NameValuePair>(2);
                    nameValuePairs.add(new BasicNameValuePair("session_id", SAMPLE_SESSION_ID));
                    nameValuePairs.add(new BasicNameValuePair("query_to_sign", "SDEelementsSampleData"));
                    httppost.setEntity(new UrlEncodedFormEntity(nameValuePairs));

                    // Execute HTTP Post Request
                    HttpResponse response = httpclient.execute(httppost);
                    HttpEntity response_entity = response.getEntity();
                    // Get the response
                    BufferedReader rd = new BufferedReader(new
                        InputStreamReader(response_entity.getContent()));
                    // And display the signature
                    String line = "";
                    while ((line = rd.readLine()) != null) {
                        Message lmsg;
                        lmsg = new Message();
                        lmsg.obj = line;
                        lmsg.what = 0;
                        AndroidSecretKeyActivity.this.h.sendMessage(lmsg);
                    }
                }
                catch (Exception e) {
                    Message lmsg = new Message();
                    lmsg.obj = Log.getStackTraceString(e);
                    lmsg.what = 0;
                    AndroidSecretKeyActivity.this.h.sendMessage(lmsg);
                }
            }

[Download the Complete Code Example](https://preview.sdelements.com/static/code/Android/AndroidSecretKey.zip)

A stand-alone demo web server is also provided to facilitate the demo test of the above application.

The server component requires python 2.4 or above. To execute, you can run:

    python demo_webserver_AndroidSecretKey.py

By default it will listen on TCP port 8008 on the host being executed on.

[Download the Complete Code Example](https://preview.sdelements.com/static/code/Android/demo_webserver_AndroidSecretKey.py)

- Java provides a KeyStore class (in 'java.security' package) that could be used to store application secrets on the client.

 - Android provides an OS-level-managed [KeyChain](http://developer.android.com/reference/android/security/KeyChain.html). Alternatively, developers can use Android Keystores (Java Keystore). See this section on [choosing between Keystore and KeyChain](http://developer.android.com/training/articles/keystore.html#WhichShouldIUse)

 - This code sample demonstrates how a certificate and a private key can be retrieved from a keystore.

````
  String keyStoreName = "MyKeyStore.ks";
  String myKeystorePassword="TEST";
  char[] pw = myKeystorePassword.toCharArray();
  FileInputStream f = new FileInputStream(keyStoreName);
  // You can also use PKCS12 keystores which are compatible with platforms
  // other than Java (if that's a concern).
  KeyStore keystore = KeyStore.getInstance("JKS");
  keystore.load(f, pw);
  // Certificate
  Certificate cert = keystore.getCertificate("certificateAlias");
  // Private key
  KeyStore.ProtectionParameter protParam =
  new KeyStore.PasswordProtection(pw);
  KeyStore.PrivateKeyEntry pkE = (KeyStore.PrivateKeyEntry) keystore.getEntry("PKAlias", protParam);
  PrivateKey pk = pkE.getPrivateKey();
````
 - JDK9 [defaults the keystore type to the PKCS12 format](https://blogs.oracle.com/jtc/jdk9-keytool-transitions-default-keystore-to-pkcs12). You can specify "PCKS12" instead of "JKS" in the code above (`KeyStore keystore = KeyStore.getInstance("PKCS12");`).

 - Since accessing the data stored in the keystore requires the use of a master-password, the application should store the master-password (of the local keystore) somewhere. This master-password should either be stored on the server (received only after proper authentication), or be derived from a user-provided password (e.g. using Password-Based Key Derivation Functions 2 (PBKDF2)).

 - In the case of PBKDF2, the result will be a key that could be used as the master-key of keystore and will depend on a user-provided password and a salt (random) value. You should store the salt on the private storage of the application (private data folders of the application) and recalculate the key when accessing the keystore using the password and the salt. The salt does not need any extra protection. Be aware that the keystore master-password in this case will be dependent on a user password, which should be considered when any password change is attempted. The following piece of code shows how `inputPassword` and `salt` could be turned into a SecretKey (sk) for keystore.

````
  char[] inputPassword={...};
  byte[] salt={...};
  SecretKeyFactory skf = SecretKeyFactory.getInstance("PBKDF2WithHmacSHA512");
  int iterations=1000;int keyLen=256;
  KeySpec params = new PBEKeySpec(inputPassword, salt, iterations, keyLen);
  SecretKey sk = skf.generateSecret(params);
````

 - You can convert the SecretKey to String and use it as keystore password ([Base64 in Android](http://developer.android.com/reference/android/util/Base64.html)):

````
  String stringSecretKey = Base64.encodeToString(sk.getEncoded(), Base64.DEFAULT)

  Similarly, in Java:

  String stringSecretKey = Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString(sk.getEncoded());
````

 See this article for guidelines on various uses of the [Android Keystore System](http://developer.android.com/training/articles/keystore.html).

There are a few instructions to follow when performing Java object serialization:

 1. Do not put confidential data in plain text in serialized data.
 2. Do not de-serialize untrusted data.
 3. Check the integrity and authenticity of serialized objects before attempting to de-serialize them.
 4. Do not use unsafe Java libraries that are provided with untrusted data. There are so many of such libraries and it is best to avoid de-serializing any untrusted data from untrusted inputs altogether.
 5. Limit the size of input data that is going to be de-serialized to avoid placing a high load on the application and causing denial of service.

 Note(s): The following site provides many resources for developers around the serialization problem,
 https://github.com/GrrrDog/Java-Deserialization-Cheat-Sheet

 Know that code in the de-serialized object e.g. `readObject()` method if implemented runs even before you cast and take control of the object. For example consider this class that needs to be serialized:

````
  import java.io.*;
  public class Person implements Serializable {
  public String name;
  public int birthYear;
  transient public int idNumber;
  Person() {
  System.out.println("In Person's Constructor.");
  }
  private void readObject(java.io.ObjectInputStream in) throws IOException, ClassNotFoundException {
  System.out.println("Implements readObject().");
  in.defaultReadObject();
  }
  void runMe() {
  System.out.println("Run Me!");
  }
  }
````
 The object can perform malicious activities in `readObject()` if you simply do this (if the data in the _fileName_ is malicious or altered):

````  
// Simple serialization that is vulnerable to code injection if used with untrusted input streams
  //...
  public static Object deserialize(String fileName) throws IOException, ClassNotFoundException {
  FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream(fileName);
  ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(fis);
  Object obj = ois.readObject();
  System.out.println("After object is read");
  ois.close();
  return obj;
  }
  //...
  Person newPerson = null;
  try {
  newPerson = (Person) deserialize(fileName);
  } catch (ClassNotFoundException | IOException e) {
  e.printStackTrace();
  }
````
 Instead this implementation, checks the size of the object, seals the object (encrypts/decrypts the data in the object), and signs it (signs the object and verifies the signature at the time of de-serialization):

````
  import java.io.*;
  import java.security.*;
  import javax.crypto.*;
  import javax.crypto.spec.*;

  public class Serialization {
  static PublicKey myPubKey; // This will be generated later
  // This key should be stored and handled securely. It is put here just for demonstration purposes:
  private static final byte[] symmetricKeyArray = "SomeText16Bytes!".getBytes(); // Do not hardcode. Just for demonstration
  private static final String cipherMode = "AES";

  public static Object deserializeSigned(String fileName)
  throws IOException, NoSuchAlgorithmException, InvalidKeyException, SignatureException, ClassNotFoundException, NoSuchPaddingException, IllegalBlockSizeException, BadPaddingException
  {
  FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream(fileName);
  Object rawObject;

  int fileLength=(int)fis.getChannel().size();
  if (fileLength>10000) {
  System.out.println("Large File!");

  rawObject=null;
  return rawObject;
  }

  System.out.println("Opening the file...");
  ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(fis);
  SignedObject signedObject = (SignedObject) ois.readObject();
  System.out.println("Stream is read!");

  Signature sig = Signature.getInstance(myPubKey.getAlgorithm());
  boolean isOK = signedObject.verify(myPubKey, sig);
  System.out.println("Checking Signature!");

  if (!isOK) {
  System.out.println("ERROR!");

  rawObject=null;
  return rawObject;
  }

  rawObject = (Object) getUnsealed((SealedObject)signedObject.getObject());

  System.out.println("After object is read");
  ois.close();
  return rawObject;
  }


  public static Object getUnsealed(SealedObject so)
  throws IOException, NoSuchAlgorithmException, InvalidKeyException, SignatureException, ClassNotFoundException, NoSuchPaddingException, IllegalBlockSizeException, BadPaddingException
  {

  SecretKeySpec sks = new SecretKeySpec(symmetricKeyArray, cipherMode);
  Cipher cipher = Cipher.getInstance(cipherMode);
  cipher.init(Cipher.DECRYPT_MODE, sks);

  Object rawObject= so.getObject(cipher);
  return rawObject;
  }

  public static void serializeSigned(Serializable obj, String fileName)
  throws IOException, NoSuchAlgorithmException, InvalidKeyException, SignatureException, NoSuchPaddingException, IllegalBlockSizeException
  {
  FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream(fileName);

  KeyPairGenerator keyPairGenerator = KeyPairGenerator.getInstance("DSA");
  KeyPairGenerator.initialize(1024, new SecureRandom());
  KeyPair keyPair = keyPairGenerator.genKeyPair();
  PrivateKey privateKey = keyPair.getPrivate();
  PublicKey publicKey = (PublicKey) keyPair.getPublic();
  myPubKey=publicKey;

  Signature signature = Signature.getInstance(privateKey.getAlgorithm());

  SignedObject signedObject = new SignedObject(getSealed(obj), privateKey, signature);

  ObjectOutputStream oos = new ObjectOutputStream(fos);
  oos.writeObject(signedObject);
  oos.close();

  fos.close();
  }

  public static SealedObject getSealed(Serializable obj)
  throws IOException, NoSuchAlgorithmException, InvalidKeyException, SignatureException, NoSuchPaddingException, IllegalBlockSizeException
  {

  SecretKeySpec sks = new SecretKeySpec(symmetricKeyArray, cipherMode);

  // Create cipher
  Cipher cipher = Cipher.getInstance(cipherMode);
  cipher.init(Cipher.ENCRYPT_MODE, sks);
  SealedObject sealedObject = new SealedObject(obj, cipher);

  return sealedObject;
  }

  public static void main(String[] args) {
  System.out.println("START OF SERIALIZATION");
  String fileName="c://tests//myFile.txt";
  Person pers = new Person();
  pers.birthYear=2000;
  pers.idNumber=1100;
  pers.name="Joe";

  try {
