If your **browser-side JavaScript** takes **user-controlled DOM properties** (specifically *location* or *referrer*) as input to create dynamic HTML content:

- Use dynamic build interfaces and safe rendering methods (i.e. methods that have command execution context) instead of unsafe rendering methods.
    - Examples of **unsafe** rendering methods are:

             element.innerHTML = "...";
             element.outerHTML = "...";
             document.write(...);
             document.writeln(...);

    - Examples of **safe** dynamic build interfaces and methods are:

            document.createElement("...")
            element.setAttributes("...", "value")
            element.appendChild(...)
            element.textContent = "...";
            element.innerText = "...";

- Do not use `setAttribute(name_string,value_string)` to set executable HTML attributes with a user-controlled `value_string`. Examples of such executable attributes are **JavaScript event handlers** such as *onclick* and *onmouseover*.

        // Vulnerable Code: Untrusted data executes even if it is properly JavaScript encoded.
        element.setAttribute("onclick", "An executable value containing untrusted data.");

- URL encode untrusted data before passing it to the CSS `url()` method.

        document.body.style.backgroundImage = "url(" + encodeURIComponent(untrustedData) + ")";

- URL encode and then JavaScript encode untrusted data before passing it to a URL attribute.

        element.setAttribute("href", encodeURIComponent(untrustedData));

- Encode the output of user-controlled data before it can be implicitly passed to an `eval()` function.

## DOM-base XSS Explanation

Some of the DOM properties can be controlled by the user and might include unsafe values. 

- An example is `document.location`. If this property is used in your dynamic JavaScript code to create HTML content in an unsafe manner, such as being assigned to `element.innerHTML`, it can allow attackers to inject script by creating malicious links. This is essentially a cross-site scripting vulnerability.

Some of the DOM properties that may be manipulated for XSS include:

     document.URL
     document.URLUnencoded
     document.location (and many of its properties)
     document.referrer
     window.location (and many of its properties)
     location (note that window.location can be access as just location)

**Note:** These properties might have unsafe sub-attributes such as `location.hash`.

For more information, see the [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet).

