## Description

 Verifying `Origin:` header in cross origin resource sharing (CORS) is not an adequate measure for access control (See Notes below). There is no guarantee that CORS requests are sent by an actual browser (which follows HTML5 protocols), and there is no guarantee that those request are not forged or manipulated. Checking origin in addition to normal authentication/authorization mechanism can prevent unintended access to data and services on the server.

- If your application's access control and session management is based on cookies (as opposed to query parameters or form fields) enable sending cookies by setting the `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` response header (from server) to 'true' (see code below).

- If the request is sent from the browser over plain HTTP channel but the origin shows HTTPS prefix do not process the message or return an error. Include both secure and non-secure versions of the website in the allowed Origin list. Here is a sample list of allowed Origins:

`Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://www.mydomain.com http://www.mydomain.com https://subdomain.anotherdomain.com http://subdomain.anotherdomain.com` 

- Use a white-list for trusted `Origin:`s. Avoid returning the request header `Origin:` value in the response header `Access-Control-Allow-Origin:` which means that you are responding to any request (Read the notes below to see the consequences). Use wildcard, `*`, in `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` only for the service that are publicly accessible and do not return any sensitive data in their return values or HTTP headers.

- Make sure you include the domain of your server in the white-list (of trusted origins), to allow accepting same-origin requests. If your server code returns an error when the `Origin` doesn't match a list of allowed domains, and your server is not in that list, same origin requests are blocked. 

- Use the response header `Access-Control-Max-Age:` to enforce a time limit on the CORS sharing period (in seconds).

- Note that according to [W3C Specifications](http://www.w3.org/TR/cors/#preflight-request) user credentials should be excluded from the preflight request. Therefore, the preflight request cannot be authenticated. You should not rely only on authentication when the request method is OPTIONS. Do authentication for any other request method (any HTTP verb such as GET and POST). 

- Based on the server's technology the above requirements are fulfilled differently. To enable CORS for your server see (this links)[http://enable-cors.org/server.html].  
 In case that you need to handle parts of the communication here is some guidelines. For example analyze the code below in PHP (the code is only demonstrative and could be modified for other target languages):

             <?php
             if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] == 'OPTIONS')
             //HTTP and HTTPS 
             if  ( ( ($_SERVER['HTTP_ORIGIN'] == "https://www.mydomain.com") 
              and (!empty($_SERVER['HTTPS']) ) ) // Check if the origin matches the connection type (SSL) 
              or
             ($_SERVER['HTTP_ORIGIN'] == "http://www.mydomain.com")
              or
             ($_SERVER['HTTP_ORIGIN'] == "http://subdomain.anotherdomain.com")
              or
             (($_SERVER['HTTP_ORIGIN'] == "https://subdomain.anotherdomain.com") 
              and (!empty($_SERVER['HTTPS']) ) 
              ) )
            {
             // List of the domains that are allowed to access our services through CORS 
             header('Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://www.mydomain.com http://www.mydomain.com https://subdomain.anotherdomain.com http://subdomain.anotherdomain.com');
             // Maximum time that the browser can cache preflight response (in seconds) 
             header('Access-Control-Max-Age: 3600');
             // Send cookies with the actual request
             header('Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true');

             }
             else // if not OPTIONS
             {              
             // Perform authentication/authorization for any request type that is not OPTIONS.
             // Check the origin and return it in the Access-Control-Allow-Origin. Send an error or empty response (with valid headers) when the origin is not trusted.
             // Note that some browsers do not send preflight requests (OPTIONS).
             // Make sure that no part of the code is reached without authentication and checking of Origin. 
              validate_origin();
              perform_authentication();

              }

             ?>

 Cookies are not sent by default. If cookies are not needed, do not set `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` header.


## A Note on CORS and Access Control

 Checking the origin, is helpful when we want to prevent a malicious website from accessing user data on our server or performing unauthorized actions. For example suppose that a malicious site (___M___) which is not trusted by our server (___S___) is visited by a genuine user (___U___). ___M___ could use CORS capabilities to request data or an action from ___S___ if it was trusted. If ___U___  has already logged into ___S___, all the session cookies are stored in ___U___'s browser, and a malicious script from ___M___ could access sensitive data made available through CORS requests and send such data to ___M___ (Note that CORS allows sending ___U___'s credentials to ___S___ which enables ___M___ to pass the authorization step and perform the actions it intends to).

 However Origin header, does not help much if the user (___U___) is a hacker. A hacker can install a plugin on the browser (or forge requests) to pretend that the CORS requests are coming from a trusted website. In that case it is the access control that can stop the hacker, from attaining unauthorized information.

Cross site request forgery (CSRF) could become a more complicated problem when combined with CORS. A trusted site (T) by your server (S) can send cross site requests that are malicious (e.g. as a result of HTML injection into that site (T)). If these requests use CORS capabilities (based on the trust that S has to T), they can divulge user information to a hacker.

For this reason, `Origin:` headers are not suitable means to avoid CSRF. Normal anti-CSRF tokens should be added to messages, and verified by the server (S). For learning how to add anti-CSRF protection to your application see the related how-tos for using anti cross site request forgery (CSRF) tokens.

If anti-CSRF method is based on cookies/sessions (as opposed to query parameters or form fields) the server side component should enable sending cookies by setting the `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` response header (from server) to 'true'. Note that cookies are not sent with preflight request (user credentials should be excluded from the preflight request according to W3C specifications).

Depending on the server's technology it is achieved differently. For example in PHP this piece of code sends the required response headers (the code is only illustrative and could be easily changed for any target language):

           <?php
           if($_SERVER['HTTP_ORIGIN'] == "http://trustedwebsite.com")
           {
            header('Access-Control-Allow-Origin: http://trustedwebsite.com');
            header('Access-Control-Max-Age: 3600');
            header('Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true');
             }
            ?>

Note that some browsers do not send OPTIONS preflight requests (`if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] == 'OPTIONS')...`). Always test your code with the major browsers and those that are supported.
Cookies are not sent by default.

