## Establishing HTTPS Connections

- Use the `HttpClient` or `URL::openConnection` interface for accessing HTTPS services. Android Marshmallow promotes obtaining `HttpURLConnection` (or HttpsURLConnection) by calling `URL.openConnection()`. The `URL::openConnection` interface is provided in `java.net.URL`. See this example:

        URL url = new URL("https://www.test.com");
        URLConnection conn = url.openConnection();

- Calling `openConnection()` with an "HTTPS" address will return an `HttpsURLConnection`. For more information, see the Android developer documentation about [HttpURLConnection](http://developer.android.com/reference/java/net/HttpURLConnection.html).

- The `HttpClient` interface is provided in `org.apache.http.client.HttpClient`. However, Android Marshmallow has discontinued supporting the Apache HTTP client. In order to use Apache HTTP APIs (if you must), specify the following in the `build.gradle` file (compile-time dependency): `android { useLibrary 'org.apache.http.legacy' }`

- See [this article](http://developer.android.com/training/articles/security-ssl.html) from the Android developer documentation for using HTTPS and SSL securely. Pay special attention to the section [Unknown certificate authority](http://developer.android.com/training/articles/security-ssl.html#UnknownCa) because it explains how to make a keystore with your trusted CAs (see the section on TrustStore below for more information).

## Validating Chain of Trust

- When overriding `TrustManager`, do __not__ bypass the super class functionality under any circumstances. Call the super class as the first step (see the code sample below).
- If the secure connection is used for non-HTTP-based protocols, the hostname of the certificate must be validated explicitly/manually against the expected host name. This can be done using `setHostnameVerifier` of the `SSLSocketFactory` prior to creating an SSL Socket, or by getting the peer certificate's host field after the session is established via `SSLSession.getPeerCertificates()` and validating it explicitly.
- All mentioned libraries use the underlying `TrustManager` to validate certificates. The default implementation of `TrustManager` performs the following validation for certificates:

     - Validates basic fields including expiry and critical extensions.
     - Follows the chain of trust until it reaches a trusted root authority as specified in the `KeyStore` (also called TrustStore). __If the KeyStore is not explicitly provided, the system's default `KeyStore` (TrustStore) is used.__ See the section on default TrustStores below.

## Sample Code

The following example demonstrates how to safely override the TrustManager class in order to ping accepted certificates in the application to a certain certificate authority/issuer.

 -- src/com/example/androidcertificatepinning/AndroidCertificatePinning.java

    ....
    @Override
    public void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {

        // This must be performed once at the start of the application to install required handlers
        try {
            SSLContext ctx = SSLContext.getInstance("TLS");
            // Use our Hardened version
            ctx.init(null, new TrustManager[] {new HardenedX509TrustManager(null)}, null);
            // Set the default SSL Factory of the application to the new instance we have created
            // All HTTPS / SSL access libraries will now use our new class instead of the system
            // default
            HttpsURLConnection.setDefaultSSLSocketFactory(ctx.getSocketFactory());
        } catch (NoSuchAlgorithmException e) {
            // Log or handle the exception accordingly
            // We exit here for safety reasons as the certificate pinning mechanism is not enabled
            System.exit(-1);
        } catch (KeyManagementException e) {
            // Log or handle the exception accordingly
            // We exit here for safety reasons as the certificate pinning mechanism is not enabled
            System.exit(-1);
        } catch (KeyStoreException e) {
            // Log or handle the exception accordingly
            // We exit here for safety reasons as the certificate pinning mechanism is not enabled
            System.exit(-1);
        }
    ....

 -- src/com/example/androidcertificatepinning/HardenedX509TrustManager.java

    public class HardenedX509TrustManager<E>
        implements X509TrustManager
    {

        private X509TrustManager standardTrustManager = null;
        // Change this to the authority you want to pin the certificate into
        public static final String TRUSTED_CA_AUTHORITY = "VeriSign\\, Inc.";

        /**
         * Constructor for EasyX509TrustManager.
         */
        public HardenedX509TrustManager( KeyStore keystore )
            throws NoSuchAlgorithmException, KeyStoreException
        {
            super();
            TrustManagerFactory factory = TrustManagerFactory.getInstance( TrustManagerFactory.getDefaultAlgorithm() );
            factory.init( keystore );
            TrustManager[] trustmanagers = factory.getTrustManagers();
            if ( trustmanagers.length == 0 )
            {
                throw new NoSuchAlgorithmException( "no trust manager found" );
            }
            this.standardTrustManager = (X509TrustManager) trustmanagers[0];
        }

        /**
         * @see javax.net.ssl.X509TrustManager#checkClientTrusted(X509Certificate[],String authType)
         */
        public void checkClientTrusted( X509Certificate[] certificates, String authType )
            throws CertificateException
        {
            standardTrustManager.checkClientTrusted( certificates, authType );
        }

        /**
         * @see javax.net.ssl.X509TrustManager#checkServerTrusted(X509Certificate[],String authType)
         */
        public void checkServerTrusted( X509Certificate[] certificates, String authType )
            throws CertificateException
        {
            standardTrustManager.checkServerTrusted( certificates, authType );

            for (X509Certificate cert : certificates) {
                String issuer_name = cert.getIssuerDN().getName();
                if (issuer_name.indexOf(",O=" + TRUSTED_CA_AUTHORITY + ",") == -1)
                    throw new CertificateException();
                Log.w("Error", issuer_name);
            }
        }

        /**
         * @see javax.net.ssl.X509TrustManager#getAcceptedIssuers()
         */
        public X509Certificate[] getAcceptedIssuers()
        {
            X509Certificate[] test = this.standardTrustManager.getAcceptedIssuers();
            return test;
