Java primitive types, including `int` and `long`are susceptible to integer wrapping (underflow/overflow). Arithmetic operations performed on the primitive types will not raise an exception in case of integer wrapping.

 There are several approaches available to mitigate the risk of integer wrapping. Following are some examples you can apply to your own projects.

 ##CODE

````
 // Test for underflow and overflow in Java 8+
 //
 public static boolean isOverFlow(int left, int right) {
  boolean result = false;
 try {
  Math.addExact(left, right);
  result = false;
  } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
  result = true;
  }
 return result;
 }

 public static boolean isUnderFlow(int left, int right) {
  boolean result = false;
 try {
  Math.subtractExact(left, right);
  result = false;
  } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
  result = true;
  }
 return result;
 }
````

A component can be registered to receive a specific type of broadcast (for example shut-down or boot completed). Then, the relevant action is implemented in the `onReceive` method:

            public class MyOperationClass extends BroadcastReceiver {
            @Override
            public void onReceive(Context context, Intent intent) {
            //... To do
            Toast toast = Toast.makeText(context,"Broadcast Received Here!",Toast.LENGTH_LONG);
            toast.show();
            ...}}

The component should then be registered in the Android manifest file:

        <receiver android:name="your.package.app.MyOperationClass" 
         android:permission="android.permission.RECEIVE_BOOT_COMPLETED" ...>
        <intent-filter>
        <action android:name="android.intent.action.BOOT_COMPLETED" />
        </intent-filter>
        </receiver>

However, this component is vulnerable to receiving an explicit intent that is not sent by system:

         Intent intent = new Intent()
         intent.setClassName("your.package.app" ,"your.package.app.MyOperationClass")
         this.sendBroadcast(intent);

You can see that the action that the broadcast receiver is performing can be triggered by the above-mentioned Intent. This is a security risk. 

The risk would be eliminated if the broadcast receiver checked the Intent action:

            public class MyOperationClass extends BroadcastReceiver {
            @Override
            public void onReceive(Context context, Intent intent) {
            if(intent.getAction().equals("android.intent.action.BOOT_COMPLETED"))
            {
            //... To do
            Toast toast = Toast.makeText(context,"Broadcast Received Here!",Toast.LENGTH_LONG);
            ....  }
            ...}}


Arbitrary components cannot send Intents with system actions, so a component cannot try to specify an action like this:

           intent.setAction("android.intent.action.ACTION_SHUTDOWN");
           this.sendBroadcast(intent);

This creates a permission denial exception when trying to broadcast this Intent. Normal applications cannot get shut-down broadcast permission.

