Java Simplified Encryption (Jasypt) has a `StrongPasswordEncryptor` class that automatically performs 100,000 iterations of the SHA-256 algorithm using a random 16 byte (128-bit) salt value. The salt value is then appended to the result of the hash and given as the result of the `encryptPassword(String)` method. A `checkPassword(String, String)` method is provided to check a plaintext password against the hashed, salted equivalent automatically.

Note that due to the number of iterations and size of the password, both of these methods are slower than most other password encryption tools. In web applications, new user registrations and authentication attempts occur infrequently in comparison to other transactions, so the net impact on performance will be minimal.

## Code

    public static boolean login (
        String username,
        String password,
        String ipAddress
    ){

        //Initiates Jasypt authenticator
        StrongPasswordEncryptor passwordEncryptor = new StrongPasswordEncryptor();

        try {
            String encryptedPassword =
                AuthenticationService.getCredential(username);
            if (passwordEncryptor.checkPassword(password, encryptedPassword)) {
                if (AuthenticationService.isUserLockedOut(username)){
                    throw new LoginException("User locked out");
                }

                return true;
            } else {
                throw new LoginException("Invalid username and/or password");
            }
        } catch (LoginException e){
            //Register the invalid authentication attempt
            AuthenticationService.registerAuthenticationFailure(
                username, ipAddress, e
            );
            return false;
        }
    }

